<TITLE> Grolsch says UK beer market in sharp decline </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 AMSTERDAM, Feb 12 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Dutch brewer Grolsch NV said on Tuesday 2007 like-for-like turnover grew 5 percent and net profit excluding one-off effects rose 19 percent, but it warned the British market was in sharp decline. Last week SABMiller, the world's second-biggest brewer, secured a 816 million euro ($1.2 billion) takeover of Grolsch, having won the support of key family shareholders who own 37 percent of the Dutch brewer. Grolsch reported 2007 net profit of 20 million euros ($29.06 million) on sales of 333 million euros, and said overall its international sales made a much higher contribution to profit. However it signalled problems in the British beer market. "The joint venture with Coors in the United Kingdom experienced another difficult year, with volume declining by more than 10 percent and a slightly reduced market share in the Premium Lager segment, a segment that is currently under severe pressure," Grolsch said in a statement. Analysts have expressed concern about the British beer market, particularly in the wake of Danish brewer Carlsberg and Dutch brewer Heineken's take over of Britain's Scottish & Newcastle. Heineken, which will take control of S&N's British operations, is seen by some to have paid too high a price. Grolsch noted volumes in other international markets grew more than 20 percent, with strong growth in Russia and Kazakhst
